AGI -&nbsp;A Japanese city has begun to mount a large network barrier in a popular viewpoint of Mount Fuji, in an attempt to discourage photos taken by an increasing number of tourists. The inhabitants of Fujikawaguchiko say they are sick of the incessant flows of visitors, mostly foreigners, who dirty, violate the rules of traffic looking for a photo of the most famous show in Japan to share on social media.
<br The workers started installing black nets of 2.5 x 20 meters on metal poles in the morning along a sidewalk in front of a minimarket. First, visitors climbed on the sidewalk to photograph the snowy mountain, which stands majestic in the sky from behind the store, creating a photogenic juxtaposition.<br> Politici and residents said that the city welcomes tourists, but complain that those who cross the road, ignore red traffic lights, park illegally and smoke outside the design areas.
&nbsp;
"It is regrettable to have it done because of some tourists who do not respect the rules," said in April a city official, stating that road signs and warnings of security guards failed to improve the situation.&nbsp; The measure is also intended to help a nearby dental clinic, where tourists sometimes park without permission and have been seen climb on the roof to take photos. The construction of the barrier itself was initially delayed due to problems in delivering the right materials, giving people a few more days to chase the perfect photo.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;A record number of foreign tourists is coming to Japan, where monthly visitors exceeded three million for the first time in March and then again in April. But as in other tourist locations, like Venice - which recently launched proof of a paid entry for daily visitors - the influx was not universally welcomed. In the ancient capital of Japan, Kyoto, locals complained of tourists annoying the famous geishes of the city.
&nbsp;
And the hikers who this summer will use the most popular route to climb Mount Fuji will have to pay 2,000 yen (about 14 euros) per head, with a maximum roof of 4,000 entrances to alleviate congestion. A new online booking system for the Yoshida mountain path was opened on Monday to ensure hikers access through a new gate, although 1,000 seats per day will be maintained for entrances in the day.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<br> Mount Fuji is covered in snow for most of the year, but during the July-September hiking season more than 220.000 visitors climb on its steep rocky slopes. Many climb during the night to see the dawn and some try to reach the peak of 3.776 meters without breaks, ferendosi accordingly.<br> Regional leaders have raised security and environmental issues related to overcrowding active volcano, symbol of Japan and a peaceful pilgrimage site. In recent weeks, even residents near other popular places of photographic interest in the region, including the so-called Fuji Dream Bridge, complained about excessive tourism.<br> A tour operator that offers day trips from Tokyo to the Mount Fuji area said to bring visitors to another nearby Lawson store, where you can admire a similar view, but nearby residents are less numerous.
